%I A395284 #23 Apr 24 2026 16:03:01
%S A395284 6,4,25,10,183,161,1126,4891,1253,250231,100462,49869178,234139657,
%T A395284 68279314
%N A395284 Smallest semiprime that produces a chain of exactly n semiprimes when repeatedly replacing m=p*q (with primes p<=q) by the decimal concatenation of p followed by q, stopping when the result is not semiprime.
%C A395284 The first term in each chain is the initial m, and the last term is the final semiprime before termination.
%C A395284 Conjecture: a(n) exists for all n.
%e A395284 For example, an initial semiprime m=25 produces the following chain of semiprimes:
%e A395284   25
%e A395284   55 (since 25=5*5)
%e A395284   511 (since 55=5*11)
%e A395284 The next term (773) is not a valid member of the chain, since it is not semiprime. The chain is exactly three terms long. No smaller semiprime m produces a chain of exactly three terms. So a(3)=25.
%e A395284 The first five chains are:
%e A395284   For n=1: 6
%e A395284   For n=2: 4, 22
%e A395284   For n=3: 25, 55, 511
%e A395284   For n=4: 10, 25, 55, 511
%e A395284   For n=5: 183, 361, 1919, 19101, 36367
%o A395284 (PARI) nextsp(k) = while(bigomega(k) != 2, k++); k;
%o A395284 g(k) = my(f=factor(k)); if (#f~ == 1, eval(concat(Str(f[1,1]), Str(f[1,1]))), eval(concat(Str(f[1,1]), Str(f[2,1]))));
%o A395284 isok(k,n) = my(list=List()); listput(list, k); for (i=2, n, k=g(k); if (bigomega(k)==2, listput(list, k), return(0))); bigomega(g(k)) != 2;
%o A395284 a(n) = my(k=nextsp(1)); while(!isok(k, n), k=nextsp(k+1)); k; \\ _Michel Marcus_, Apr 19 2026
%Y A395284 Cf. A001358, A106554.
%K A395284 nonn,base,more,new
%O A395284 1,1
%A A395284 _Philip Jameson_, Apr 18 2026
%E A395284 a(12)-a(14) from _Michel Marcus_, Apr 19 2026
